      <h2 class="sci-section-title">Why functional mushrooms work</h2>
      <div class="sci-two-col">
        <div class="sci-text-col">
          <p>Functional mushrooms aren't psychedelic. Lion's Mane, Cordyceps and Red Reishi are culinary and traditional-use mushrooms that have been part of Asian food and wellness practice for centuries, and they're among the most studied species in the category.</p>
          <p>The compounds researchers focus on are <strong>beta-glucans</strong> (water-soluble polysaccharides) and <strong>triterpenes</strong> (fat-soluble). Which ones actually end up in your can comes down to how the mushroom is grown and how it's extracted — the two things this page is about.</p>
          <p>The old problem was format. Capsules that taste like dirt are easy to forget. We put real fruiting-body extract into a sparkling drink you'd want anyway — at work, before the gym, or instead of a beer.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sci-cards-col">
          <div class="sci-compound-card">
            <strong>Beta-Glucans</strong>
            <p>Water-soluble polysaccharides, and the compound class most functional-mushroom research is built on. Only released by hot water extraction.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="sci-compound-card">
            <strong>Triterpenes</strong>
            <p>Fat-soluble compounds, most concentrated in Red Reishi. Hot water leaves them behind — they need an alcohol extraction to come out.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="sci-compound-card">
            <strong>Cordycepin</strong>
            <p>The compound Cordyceps is best known for, and the reason it's the mushroom athletes reach for. An adenosine analog — not a stimulant.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

